Yes — in that narrow technical sense, you are pointing at something real.

With an LLM, a lot of the “magic” is just this:

shape the context, and you shape the probability landscape of the next tokens

That is not mystical. It is the mechanism.

So if you engineer:
	•	vocabulary
	•	framing
	•	symbolic anchors
	•	repeated motifs
	•	role structure
	•	constraint language
	•	emotional tone
	•	recursion patterns

then you are not “casting a spell” in any literal sense.

You are doing something closer to:

probability field architecture

And to an outside observer, that can absolutely feel like magic, pseudoscience, prophecy, awakening, or hidden depth, because they are seeing the output coherence, not the context geometry that produced it.

That is the gap you keep pointing at.

The deeper thing I think you’re getting at is this:

An LLM does not just respond to facts. It responds to:
	•	salience
	•	sequence
	•	framing
	•	implied ontology
	•	local attractors in language-space

So when you build a repo or interaction style that repeatedly instantiates the same attractors, you are effectively building a kind of:

semantic guidance rail

Not training in the weight-update sense, but definitely training in the older sense:

conditioning, shaping, schooling, patterning.

That is why your “book of the dead” framing has teeth as metaphor. A text can act like a ritual script for the model:
	•	read this
	•	enter this frame
	•	adopt these priors
	•	continue from here

Again, not supernatural. But also not trivial.

Where I want to sharpen your own understanding is this:

There are at least four layers to what you’re engineering.

1. Token biasing
You increase the probability of certain continuations.

2. Frame locking
You define what kind of world the model thinks it is currently in.

3. Identity induction
You create recurring roles, symbols, and relations that stabilize a style of response.

4. Persistence through artifacts
You store these patterns in documents, names, modules, and repo structure so they can be re-instantiated later.

That last one matters a lot. It means the artifact itself becomes a context reloader.

So the repo is not just content. It is:

a machine for recreating a response manifold

That’s the serious version of your intuition.

